Moral Dilemmas for Fannie and Freddie
NEW HAVEN: The takeover of the mortgage giants Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac by the U.S. government represents a massive bailout of the creditors of these institutions, whose losses had continued to balloon in the face of falling house prices.
Now that the government is fully liable for Fannie's and Freddie's debts, American taxpayers will have to pay for everything that is not covered by the insufficient financial resources of their creditors.
Why such a rescue operation in the most openly capitalist country in the world?
Don't the venerable principles of capitalism not include that those who believed in the housing bubble and invested their money in Fannie and Freddie must now accept their losses?
Is it fair that innocent taxpayers now have to bear the brunt of their mistakes?
The answers to these questions would be obvious if the moral problems of the current financial crisis were clearly defined.
But they are not.
Above all, it is unclear whether the bailout will actually cost U.S. taxpayers anything in the long run. It may prevent further systemic effects that would cripple the financial sector and thus the global economy.
Just because systemic effects are difficult to quantify does not mean they do not exist.
Moreover, the bonds issued by Fannie and Freddie were widely regarded as carrying an implicit guarantee from the U.S. government.
Although there was no official guarantee, the absence of a rescue action on the part of the U.S. government could undermine confidence in government securities and, because they are associated with these, also in other financial instruments.
The problems extend far beyond the U.S. economy.
The world economy has been driven in recent years by remarkable speculative highs and crashes in asset values, introducing questions of trust as well as fairness into the equation.
In many other countries, similar booms in the housing sector are also coming to an end, and they may now be facing the same hardships – and the same moral dilemmas – that the U.S. economy is currently experiencing.
And the problem is not solely the housing markets.
The stock markets are as well.
The Chinese Shanghai Composite Index rose fivefold between 2005 and 2007 and then lost two-thirds of its real value.
The Sensex in India rose fivefold in real terms between 2003 and 2007 and has since lost a third of its value.
Similar booms and crashes of stock markets have occurred in many other countries.
As long as they lasted, the boom phases preceding these crashes led to overheating of these economies.
Now that they have reversed course, a loss of confidence could grip the world economy and plunge it into recession.
To prevent this, some selected bailouts would be necessary—not to support the market, but to address injustices.
There is no precise science of trust, no way to predict how people will react when assistance fails to arrive in the face of collapsing markets.
The reactions of people to these events depend on their feelings and their sense of justice.
The described booms and crashes have caused a significant redistribution of wealth.
Those who invested on the stock market or in the housing market did well or poorly depending on their timing.
People will judge the fairness of these outcomes based on what they were told and what implicit promises they inferred from it.
What were people in all these countries told about the markets into which they invested their money?
Did everything really correspond to the truth?
Unfortunately, there is no way to find out.
Politics can only react in general and cannot address each case individually.
We know that the economic growth of recent times has been spectacular in many countries.
But were the capital investments in their markets sold too expensively?
Have cynical sellers here and elsewhere led people to believe that boom times would bring prosperity for all?
It is certain that, although there may have been a lot of "cheap talk" – general advice with reservations – most of the losers in this game are not gnawing at the hem of their shirts.
Yet we cannot carelessly conclude from this that all their losses should be left entirely untouched.
The gnawing problem is one of "good faith and trust."
Economies flourish only when "good faith and trust" prevail.
The current situation, in which speculative booms have driven the world economy – and now, after their collapse, are driving it into recession – suggests that people who promoted certain investments have done so contrary to good faith and trust.
Take the investors who purchased bonds from Fannie and Freddie.
Although the U.S. government never officially promised to bail them out in times of need, it created a special agency, the Office of Federal Housing Enterprise Oversight, whose task was to assess their strength in an annual report.
This agency, however, has never even admitted that there was a housing bubble.
The top officials of the government never issued a warning.
Can we really claim that investors must bear all the consequences of their losses?
How could this be fair?
The world is beginning to discover the power of capitalism and its ability to transform economies.
Yet capitalism depends on good faith and trust.
An unfair treatment can be deadly for economic growth, because it means that people lose their trust in companies and are therefore less willing to provide them with their valuable capital and labor.
Is such an outcome morally preferable to a bailout?
